  "signature": "ed25519:9b2e4a1c7f3d6b0e5a8c2f4d7b1e3a6c9f2b5d8e1a4c7f0b3d6e9a2c5f8b1d4e7",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/sqa-level2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is a commercially validated FEA solver with documented software quality assurance per ISO 9001. The FDA in-house model was developed under a documented QA framework including version control (Git), peer review of all analysis scripts, and regression testing against benchmark problems. DePuy Synthes model was developed under 21 CFR Part 820 design controls. All three codes produce internally consistent results. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds required Gradation 2 for Medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/code-verification-level2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical has been verified against NAFEMS benchmark problems for structural mechanics including beam bending, contact, and large-displacement scenarios. The FDA model was verified against three analytical solutions: Euler-Bernoulli beam theory for the rod, Hertzian contact for screw-rod interface, and published closed-form solutions for implant stiffness. All verification residuals < 1% of reference solution. Code verification is documented in the FDA OSEL modeling report v3.2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/discretization-level2",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study performed on the non-cannulated screw-rod construct using three refinement levels (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements). Richardson extrapolation applied to stiffness, yield force, and force-at-40mm QoIs. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) < 1.2% for all QoIs at the medium mesh, which was selected for the production ensemble runs. Convergence is monotonic and in the asymptotic range (GCI_fine/GCI_medium ratio within 5% of theoretical value of 4 for second-order elements)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/solver-error-level2",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear Newton-Raphson solver used with force residual tolerance of 1e-4 and displacement residual tolerance of 1e-4. Residual convergence plots reviewed for all 33 simulation runs (3 models × 11 specimen geometries); no convergence anomalies detected. Contact stabilization energy monitored and confirmed < 0.1% of total strain energy in all runs. Iterative solver (PCG with incomplete Cholesky preconditioner) cross-checked against direct sparse solver on three representative cases; maximum QoI discrepancy < 0.05%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/use-error-level2",
      "rationale": "All three modeling teams followed a pre-registered simulation plan specifying boundary conditions, material property assignment, contact definitions, and post-processing procedures before model execution. Independent peer review of each team's setup files was conducted by a fourth analyst not involved in model construction. A documented simulation execution checklist was completed and archived for each of the 33 runs. No deviations from the simulation plan were identified during review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-form-level3",
      "rationale": "The continuum finite element representation of the pedicle screw, rod, and set screw assembly captures the dominant physics: elastic-plastic material behavior of titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V), large-displacement geometric nonlinearity, and frictional contact at screw-rod interfaces (μ = 0.2, consistent with published tribological data for Ti-Ti interfaces). Viscoelastic and rate-dependent effects are negligible for quasi-static ASTM F1717 loading at 5 mm/min. Fluid effects are absent. Bone analog (UHMWPE) is represented as linear elastic, validated separately. Model form uncertainty is bounded by the ensemble spread across three independent modeling approaches."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-inputs-level3",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V (E = 114 GPa, σ_y = 880 MPa, tangent modulus from coupon testing) and UHMWPE (E = 0.93 GPa) sourced from lot-specific material certificates for the tested lots. Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of each of the 11 test specimens (dimensional uncertainty ± 0.01 mm). Friction coefficient characterized by dedicated pin-on-disk testing on representative surface finish specimens. Torque applied to set screw quantified by calibrated torque wrench with ± 2% accuracy and propagated as an input uncertainty. All inputs documented in the model input traceability matrix (MITM-001)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-samples-level3",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested: 6 at Lab 1 (FDA OSEL), 5 at Lab 2 (independent ISO 17025 accredited laboratory). All specimens from the same production lot as the device under submission, with full material traceability. Sample size determined a priori by power analysis targeting 80% power to detect a 10% QoI difference at α = 0.05 given expected coefficient of variation of 5%. Between-laboratory variability characterized and incorporated into the validation uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test conditions factor scoped out following a documented marginal-call deliberation. The ASTM F1717 protocol specifies a single standardized test configuration (offset distance, loading rate, temperature) with no provision for multi-condition variation; all 11 specimens were tested under identical protocol conditions. The credibility team considered whether testing at a second loading rate or offset distance would add informative coverage but concluded: (1) the COU is specifically bounded to ASTM F1717 quasi-static protocol conditions as stated in the intendedUse field — extrapolation to other loading rates or configurations is explicitly out of scope for this submission; (2) the single-condition limitation is fully disclosed in the COU description and accepted by the decision authority as a known scope boundary rather than an uncontrolled gap; (3) the model risk level (3) and Medium assurance target do not mandate multi-condition coverage when the COU is itself defined around a single standardized test; (4) analogous FDA-cleared submissions for pedicle screw systems (e.g., 510(k) K192345, K203218) accepted single-condition F1717 validation as sufficient for the same device class and COU. The scope-out is therefore a deliberate, documented boundary condition of the COU rather than an unaddressed weakness. The factor is not assessed; its contribution to the credibility argument is replaced by the explicit COU boundary statement and the regulatory precedent cited above."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/input-equivalency-level3",
      "rationale": "Specimen-specific FEA models were constructed for each of the 11 test constructs using CMM-measured geometry, lot-specific material properties, and measured assembly torques. Input parameter equivalency between simulation and physical test is therefore established at the individual specimen level, not merely at the population mean level. The MITM-001 traceability matrix maps each simulation input to its experimental measurement source with documented uncertainty. No systematic offsets between nominal and as-built dimensions were detected (maximum deviation 0.03 mm, within measurement uncertainty)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/output-comparison-level3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/u_val for each of the three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) across all 11 specimens and three modeling teams (99 paired comparisons total). All E/u_val ratios < 1.96, satisfying the pre-established acceptance criterion. Maximum E/u_val = 1.71 (yield force, Lab 2, FDA model). Mean absolute percentage error across all comparisons = 4.3% (well within the 10% acceptance bound). Validation uncertainty u_val incorporates experimental measurement uncertainty, between-laboratory variability, and simulation numerical uncertainty via RSS combination. Results summarized in validation result objects vr-stiffness-ensemble, vr-yield-force-ensemble, and vr-force-at-40mm."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/qoi-relevance-level2",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the primary outputs specified by ASTM F1717 and are directly relevant to the clinical failure modes of concern (fatigue crack initiation driven by cyclic stress, and acute fracture). Stiffness governs load sharing with the vertebral column; yield force bounds the onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm characterizes post-yield energy absorption. All three QoIs are directly predicted by the FEA model and directly measured in the bench test, with no intermediate transformation required. The QoI set covers the full envelope of the COU decision basis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/validation-relevance-level3",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is a direct comparison of the FEA model to physical bench tests of the same device design, same material lot, same assembly procedure, and same test protocol (ASTM F1717) as specified in the COU. The validation domain is therefore identical to the application domain — there is no extrapolation required. Between-laboratory testing at two ISO 17025 accredited facilities confirms that results are not laboratory-specific artifacts. The validation activities were designed prospectively to address the COU claims, as documented in the pre-registered simulation and test plan (STP-NONCANNULATED-001, dated prior to test execution)."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-2024",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team accepts the FEA modeling framework for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw ASTM F1717 compression-bending COU at Medium assurance level. Twelve of the thirteen V&V 40 factors were formally assessed; eleven achieved their required credibility level or above, and one (Test conditions) was scoped out with documented rationale tied to the explicit COU boundary. The validation metric E/u_val < 1.96 was satisfied for all three QoIs across all 99 paired simulation-experiment comparisons, with maximum E/u_val = 1.71 and mean absolute percentage error of 4.3%. The ensemble approach across three independent modeling teams (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) provides additional confidence that results are not model-specific artifacts. Model risk level 3 and Medium decision consequence (revision surgery, not mortality) are consistent with the Medium assurance target. The scoped-out Test conditions factor is accepted as a COU boundary condition supported by regulatory precedent for this device class and does not constitute an unaddressed credibility gap. The provenance chain from raw experimental data through simulation inputs to QoI comparisons is fully documented and traceable. Decision: Accepted for the stated COU.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
